Exercise 1 (R code and outputs required)

1

Using information that you just produced from the scatterplots, correlation table, and vif, are there any variables you are concerned about including together in the same linear model? In other words, which variables do you think would lead to multi-collinearity in your model? Why? I worry about including these following variables together in the same linear model. Because they are too correlate.

temperature and elevation Rain and elevation temperature and rain

Correlation values of these variables are > 0.5. In the scatter plot, temperature and elevation, rain and elevation as well as temperature and rain seem to be related. The vif value of temperature is greater than 5.

2

What are the two most correlated variables you see in the correlation table produced using cor? Please run two separate univariate models where Yield is your dependent variable and one of the two correlated variables is your predictor variable. Now run a multivariate regression with Yield as your dependent variable and both of your correlated variables as pedictor variables in the same model. Compare the beta coefficients you get for each of the two predictor variables in the univariate model and the multivariate model. Are they the same? Are they different? Why?

temperature and elevation

Because temperature and elevation are to related and lead to multi-collinearity.

Exercise 2 (Some R code and outputs required)

fullmod <- lm(Yield ~ Canal_Dist + Irrigated_Per + Literate + Cultivator + AgLabor + Rain + Temperature + Elevation + SowDate, data = yield)
fullmod2 <- lm(Yield ~ Canal_Dist + Irrigated_Per + Literate + Cultivator + AgLabor + Temperature + SowDate, data = yield)
smallmod <- lm(Yield ~ Canal_Dist + Irrigated_Per + Temperature + SowDate, data = yield)
AIC(fullmod2)
## [1] 2275.772
AIC(smallmod)
## [1] 2477.5

1

Which model would you select considering the AIC values shown above? fullmodel2, because it has a lowere AIC value.

2

Please test the assumptions of normality and homoscedasticity of this model. Do you think there are problems with either normality or homoscedasticity of the residuals? Why or why not?

normality

qqPlot(residuals(fullmod2),id=FALSE)

shapiro.test(residuals(fullmod2))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  residuals(fullmod2)
## W = 0.99425, p-value = 0.7778

Most part of residuals fall within the dotted blue lines, and p-value is larger than 0.05. So the null hypothsis that errors are normally distributed is not rejected. Residuals are normally distributed.

homoscedasticity

library(zoo)
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
library(car)
library(lmtest)
bptest(fullmod2)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  fullmod2
## BP = 19.046, df = 7, p-value = 0.008045
ncvTest(fullmod2)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 8.052352, Df = 1, p = 0.0045445

Both of these results show that our p-value is below 0.05, therefore we reject the null hypothesis of homoscedasticity, and our residuals are not homoscedastic.
